Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)
Q: What are the general admission requirements for US universities?

A: Admission requirements vary by university and program. Generally, you need a high school diploma or equivalent, standardized test scores (e.g., SAT, ACT), proof of English proficiency (e.g., TOEFL, IELTS), and letters of recommendation. Qadri-international can help you understand and meet the specific requirements of your chosen institutions.

Q: How much does it cost to study in USA?

A: Tuition fees in the USA vary widely depending on the university and program. On average, international undergraduate students can expect to pay between $20,000 and $50,000 per year. Additionally, living costs range from $10,000 to $20,000 per year. Scholarships, grants, and financial aid are available to help manage these expenses.

Q: Can international students work while study in USA?

A: Yes, international students on an F-1 visa can work up to 20 hours per week on-campus during term time and full-time during holidays. There are also opportunities for internships and practical training related to your field of study.

Q: How do I apply for a US student visa?

A: After being accepted by a US university, you can apply for an F-1 student visa. You’ll need a Form I-20 from your university, proof of financial resources, and other supporting documents. Qadri-international can guide you through the visa application process, ensuring you have all the necessary documentation and information.
